But if, indeed, these enmities be changed into friendship, (for both times and disposition do often change,) and the Spaniards be desirous of gratifying the Portugueze, let them grant them the spacious plains void of inhabitants and of colonieS, with our free leave. What! shall we give up our towns to the Portugueze, by whose ancestors so many thousands of our countrymen have been either slain, or forced into cruel slavery in Brazil ?—We can neither suffer nor believe it. When, embracing Christianity, we swore alle- giance to God and the Catholic King, the priests and royal governours with one voice pro- mised us the friendship and protection of the king: now, though guilty of no crime, and de- serving every good return sor our serviceS, we are constrained to expatriate,a punishment most grievous, and almost intolerable.
